BCC Protégé Variants

What constitutes a variant?

The primary goal when determining variants was to make classifications based on what an average player could readily identify as 'different'. As a result, a chipper may further identify discrepancies within a variant, but these will be relatively minor. Buttons and plaques follow a similar protocol for identifying variants (although the concept is far less relevant there). Any deviation from standard sizing also constitutes a new variant, regardless of the other characteristics.

Variant-inducing factors:

  • Large discrepancies in clay colors, and which are basically consistent across many chips
  • Differences with inlay font size and/or color
  • Inlay 'size' - the perceived area consumed by the inlay's graphic and/or text elements
  • Chip diameter discrepancies
  • Slight increase in chip thickness which mandate 67.7mm racks.

Variant-local factors:

  • Minor discrepancies in clay colors
  • Varying print quality in the inlay

Info

  • Final design by William R. Coughlan (Magus_23).
  • Design process was 'by committee' comprising of members from ChipTalk.net. The design process took approximately 9 months.
  • Produced by Blue Chip Company for Sidepot.
  • Features the Cigar & Snifter mold.
  • Supplemental variants were produced a single time. All the primary chips had multiple production runs.
  • The primary denominations produced with the supplementals are sometimes identifiable because of their inlay differences.
  • Almost every variant will fit snugly in 66.7mm racks. Those requiring 67.7mm are noted.
  • 24 chip denominations.
  • 55 known chip variants.
  • 8 known button variants.
  • 13 known plaque variants.
